"Every piece of knowledge must have a single, unambeguous, authoritative representation within a system" - The pragmatic programmer

The DRY principle encourages you to avoid duplicating logic, behavior, or knowledge.
It applies not only to code, but also to:
	Business rules
	Configuration
	Data models
	Documentation
	Tests

Whenever the same concept appears more than one place, we make our code redundant and that redundancy makes our system harder to maintain, vulnerable and prone to bug.
Ask yourself a question: If i need to change this logic, how many places do I need to change? will I remember all those places? If not, then apply DRY.
Now to apply DRY, simply create a utility class, write the logic there and use it everywhere.
	For example: 
	There are 3 system(authentication, payment, messaging) where we need to validate the email of a user. In future, suppose there is a new additional validation logic to email validation, how hard will it for you to add this logic to all 3 places, missing even one will cause a bug in your system. The solution is just to create a utility class, define the logic there and then use it everywhere.

When is it okay to repeat?
1. Avoid premature abstraction : abstraction created too early can be misleading or hard to maintain
	ex: 
	Earlier you see this duplication:

		if (email == null || !email.contains("@")) {
		    throw new Error();
		}

		if (adminEmail == null || !adminEmail.contains("@")) {
		    throw new Error();
		}

	Later you abstracted it(premature abstraction):

		void validateEmail(String email) {
		    if (email == null || !email.contains("@")) {
		        throw new Error();
		    }
		}

	Now the change in business rule arrived:
		- Admin email must end with @company.com
		- User email can be anything

	Now we end up doing this
		void validateEmail(String email, boolean isAdmin) {
		    if (isAdmin) {
		        if (!email.endsWith("@company.com")) throw new Error();
		    } else {
		        if (!email.contains("@")) throw new Error();
		    }
		}

		- this function lies, suppose in future a new requirement comes in, we will end up changing this GOD method
		- instead what we have done is like below in utility class which could have been maintainable and very easy to grasp

		void validateUserEmail(String email) {
		    if (email == null || !email.contains("@")) {
		        throw new Error();
		    }
		}

		void validateAdminEmail(String email) {
		    if (email == null || !email.endsWith("@company.com")) {
		        throw new Error();
		    }
		}

	- Remember below rules:
		1. If you don’t know how something will change, don’t combine it.
		2. Before making a common function, ask:
			Will these always follow the same rules?
			Will they change together?
			If you’re not sure → keep them separate.

2. If a line of code is extremely simple and unlikely to change, it may be better to repeat it rather than create a new layer of indirection.
	suppose two services A and B are there which uses a common shared method(which obeys above rule), A and B both are different yet we are adding a new layer of indirection that we could have simply avoided it.

=============================
Repetation is good if
=============================
1. Different things that look similar
	createUser()
	createAdmin()
	Are these doing different jobs? yes, then repeat

2. You’re not sure how it will change
	Do I clearly know future rules? if no, repeat

3. Logic belongs to different areas
	order validation
	shipment validation
	Are these in different features or modules? if yes, repeat

4. Condition-based helper starts appearing
	if (type == A) ...
	else if (type == B) ...
	immediately stop DRY here

5. Code is more readable duplicated
	if code is more readable than calling a generic function, then duplicate it

