The WET principle ("Write Everything Twice") and the "Rule of Three" are concepts in software development that offer guidelines for handling code duplication, contrasting with the famous DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle. WET code embraces duplication initially, while the Rule of Three suggests waiting until code appears a third time before refactoring to abstract it, allowing for better understanding of true patterns and avoiding premature abstraction. Both WET and Rule of Three acknowledge that some initial repetition is natural and helpful for understanding requirements before committing to a complex abstraction. 
